            <p>ΜΝΜΑΔΙΑΦΕΡΟΝΤ<lb/>ΑΒΑΒΑΕΙΝΚΑΙΕΖΙΚΙ<lb/>ΑΝΑΝΕΨΙΟΙϹΕΙΑΚΚ<lb/>ΩΖΩΝΟϹ</p>
         </div>
         <div type="edition"
              ana="#b1"
              xml:lang="grc"
              subtype="transcription"
              xml:id="iopp0001.transcription"
              corresp="#iopp0001.diplomatic #iopp0001.translation">
            <p>
               <choice>
                  <sic>Μνμα</sic>
                  <corr>Μνῆμα</corr>
               </choice> διαφέροντ<lb/>α Βαβαειν καὶ Ἐζικί<lb/>αν ἀνεψιοῖς
                    Εἰσὰκ Κ<lb/>ώζωνος</p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation"
              ana="#b1"
              xml:id="iopp0001.translation"
              corresp="#iopp0001.diplomatic #iopp0001.transcription">
            <p>The tomb belonging to Babaeis and Ezekias, cousins (or nephews) of Isaac
                    Kozon(?)</p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>Shallow incised white limestone slab from Jaffa. The inscription is a Jewish tombstone from a multiple burial. The front and back faces of the slab are smoothed while the edges are rough. The top of the stone is broken, but the text is still intact. A menorah without a base is inscribed in the middle of line 3, between the letters psi and iota. The word διαφέρειν is taken in the later sense of "belong to" which is well attested in patristic literature and papyri. It is not certain what exactly the author intends by the use of the term, that is, whether Babaeis and Ezekias were buried in the tomb or simply the owners of the plot. The inscription contains spelling and grammatical mistakes. The forms of the names provided, meanwhile, are difficult to discern. The names Isaac and Ezikias are relatively common in this area. While the name Babaeis is not attested elsewhere in this exact form, the forms Babi/e and Baba are both attested (biblically, in Josephus, and elsewhere). In these instances the context is Jewish/Christian, though pagan forms which seem to be from a different root do exist. Finally, the author indicates that the case and origin of the name or patronymic Κωζωνος are unclear. Though several possible parallels exist, they are attested in places and times very remote from Ioppe. The editor note that Isaac was probably mentioned on the tomb either because of his importance, because he arranged the burial, or even because he himself was buried there. From the third century onwards, the word ἀνεψιοῖς takes on the meaning of nephew in addition to its earlier meaning of cousin. The engraver uses lunate sigmas as well as a large minuscule omega (rather than a majuscule omega).</p>
         </div>
